"210":{"department":"PHYSICS","number":"210","title":"Advanced Mechanics (PHYSICS 110)","description":"Lagrangian and Hamiltonian mechanics. Principle of least action, Euler-Lagrange equations.  Small oscillations and beyond.  Symmetries, canonical transformations, Hamilton-Jacobi theory, action-angle variables.  Introduction to classical field theory.  Selected other topics, including nonlinear dynamical systems, attractors, chaotic motion.  Undergraduates register for Physics 110 (4 units). Graduates register for Physics 210 (3 units).  Prerequisites: MATH 131P, and PHYSICS 112 or MATH elective 104 or higher.  Recommended prerequisite: PHYSICS 130.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":122677,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Hartnoll, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Hartnoll, S."],"location":"530-127"}],"id":15682}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"211":{"department":"PHYSICS","number":"211","title":"Continuum Mechanics","description":"Elasticity, fluids, turbulence, waves, gas dynamics, shocks, and MHD plasmas. Examples from everyday phenomena, geophysics, and astrophysics.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":122712,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Doniach, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Doniach, S."],"location":"Hewlett Teaching Center Rm 101"}],"id":34953}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"212":{"department":"PHYSICS","number":"212","title":"Statistical Mechanics","description":"Principles, ensembles, statistical equilibrium. Thermodynamic functions, ideal and near-ideal gases. Fluctuations. Mean-field description of phase-transitions and associated critical exponents. One-dimensional Ising model and other exact solutions. Renormalization and scaling relations. Prerequisites: PHYSICS 131, 171, or equivalents.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":217438,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Shenker, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"3:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Shenker, S."],"location":""}],"id":46270}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"216":{"department":"PHYSICS","number":"216","title":"Back of the Envelope Physics","description":"Techniques such as scaling and dimensional analysis, useful to make order-of-magnitude estimates of physical effects in different settings. Goals are to promote a synthesis of physics through solving problems, including problems that are not usually thought of as physics. Applications include properties of materials, fluid mechanics, geophysics, astrophysics, and cosmology. Prerequisites: undergraduate mechanics, statistical mechanics, electricity and magnetism, and quantum mechanics.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":122714,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Madejski, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"10:20:00 AM","instructors":["Madejski, G."],"location":"Hewlett Teaching Center 102"}],"id":16536}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture","secondary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Anantua, R."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"5:50:00 PM","instructors":["Anantua, R."],"location":"160-328"}],"id":28256}],[],[]],"secondary_type":"Discussion"},
